'We Were Curiosities': One Of 'The Last Negroes At Harvard' Shares His StoryEnlarge this image toggle caption Houghton Mifflin Harcourt Houghton Mifflin HarcourtKent Garrett Sr., 97, still remembers how proud and happy he was when his son was admitted to Harvard in 1959.
His son, also named Kent Garrett, was among an unprecedented group of 18 black students accepted into the class of 1963.
Enlarge this image toggle caption Houghton Mifflin Harcourt Houghton Mifflin Harcourt"We would be attending a school that was founded and funded on the backs of our enslaved forebears ..." Garrett writes.
The 18 black students had been accepted in an early form of affirmative action.
Enlarge this image toggle caption Houghton Mifflin Harcourt Houghton Mifflin HarcourtGarrett's thinking was influenced by a roommate at Harvard who moved to Africa after college.